CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) is a stylesheet language used to describe the presentation of a document written in HTML or XML.

| Method or Keyword | When to use | One-line code syntax example |
|-------------------|-------------|-----------------------------|
| @import           | To include styles from another stylesheet | @import 'styles.css'; |
| media queries     | To apply styles based on device characteristics | @media (max-width: 600px) { ... } |
| flexbox           | To create flexible layouts | display: flex; |

- Remember that CSS can be cached by browsers, improving load times.
- Use classes for reusable styles instead of inline styles.

```css
body {
  font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
}
```

The Box model is a rectangular box that wraps around every HTML element, determining its dimensions and spacing.

| Method or Keyword | When to use | One-line code syntax example |
|-------------------|-------------|-----------------------------|
| content           | Actual content of the box | `div { content: 'Hello'; }` |
| padding           | Space between content and border | `div { padding: 10px; }` |
| border            | Surrounds the padding | `div { border: 1px solid black; }` |
| margin            | Space outside the border | `div { margin: 20px; }` | 

- Remember: Content is inside, padding is next, then border, and finally margin is outside.

```css
div {
  width: 100px;
  height: 100px;
  padding: 10px;
  border: 5px solid black;
  margin: 20px;
}
```

A CSS selector is the part of a CSS ruleset that actually selects the content you want to style.

| Method or Keyword          | When to use                          | One-line code syntax example          |
|----------------------------|--------------------------------------|---------------------------------------|
| Universal Selector         | To select all elements on a page    | `* { color: green; }`                |
| Element Type Selector      | To match HTML elements by name      | `ul { list-style: none; }`           |
| Class Selector             | To select elements by class          | `.classname { color: blue; }`        |
| ID Selector                | To select a single element by ID     | `#idname { font-size: 20px; }`      |
| Attribute Selector         | To select elements with specific attributes | `[type='text'] { border: 1px solid; }` |
| Pseudo-class Selector      | To select elements based on their state | `a:hover { color: red; }`           |

- Use the universal selector for global styles.
- Class selectors are reusable for multiple elements.
- ID selectors are unique and should be used for single elements.

```css
* {
  color: green;
  font-size: 20px;
}
ul {
  list-style: none;
  border: solid 1px ccc;
}
```

A CSS Preprocessor is a tool used to extend the basic functionality of default vanilla CSS through its own scripting language. It helps us to use complex logical syntax like variables, functions, mixins, code nesting, and inheritance to name a few, supercharging your vanilla CSS.

| Method or Keyword | When to use | One-line code syntax example |
|-------------------|--------------|------------------------------|
| Variables          | To store values for reuse | `$primary-color: #333;` |
| Mixins             | To create reusable styles | `@mixin border-radius($radius) { border-radius: $radius; }` |
| Nesting           | To organize CSS selectors hierarchically | `nav { ul { margin: 0; } }` |

- Use variables for consistent styling.
- Mixins can simplify repetitive styles.
- Nesting improves readability.

```scss
$primary-color: #333;
nav {
  ul {
    margin: 0;
    color: $primary-color;
  }
}
```

VHVW are CSS units used to size elements relative to the viewport's dimensions.

| Method or Keyword | When to use | One-line code syntax example |
|-------------------|--------------|-----------------------------|
| vh                | Use for height relative to the viewport | `height: 50vh;` |
| vw                | Use for width relative to the viewport  | `width: 50vw;` |

- 1vh is 1% of the viewport height.
- 1vw is 1% of the viewport width.

```css
.element {
  height: 50vh;
  width: 50vw;
}
```

1. Inline elements do not start on a new line and only take as much width as necessary. Inline-block elements can have width and height but still sit inline. Block elements start on a new line and take the full width available.

| Method or Keyword | When to use | One-line code syntax example |
|-------------------|-------------|-----------------------------|
| display: block    | For elements that should take the full width and start on a new line | `element { display: block; }` |
| display: inline   | For elements that should sit inline with text | `element { display: inline; }` |
| display: inline-block | For elements that need to be inline but also have width/height | `element { display: inline-block; }` | 

- Remember: Block = new line, Inline = same line, Inline-block = inline with dimensions.

```css
.block-element {
  display: block;
}

.inline-element {
  display: inline;
}

.inline-block-element {
  display: inline-block;
}
```

Cascading refers to how browsers resolve conflicts between multiple CSS rules. When multiple styles apply to an element, the browser uses a set of rules to determine which style takes precedence.

| Method or Keyword | When to use | One-line code syntax example |
|-------------------|--------------|-----------------------------|
| !important         | To override other styles | `color: white !important;` |

- Remember that the last defined style usually takes precedence.
- Specificity matters: more specific selectors win over less specific ones.

```css
p {
  color: black;
}
p {
  color: white !important;
}
```

1. border-box includes the content, padding, and border in the width and height properties, while content-box only includes the content.

| Method or Keyword | When to use | One-line code syntax example |
|-------------------|--------------|------------------------------|
| content-box       | Default box-sizing, excludes padding and border | `box-sizing: content-box;` |
| border-box        | Includes padding and border in width/height | `box-sizing: border-box;` |

- Remember: content-box = content only.
- border-box = content + padding + border.

```css
div {
  width: 300px;
  height: 200px;
  padding: 15px;
  border: 5px solid grey;
  box-sizing: border-box;
}
```

The z-index property determines the order in which elements are stacked on the z-axis. Elements with a higher z-index are displayed in front of those with a lower z-index.

| Method or Keyword | When to use | One-line code syntax example |
|-------------------|-------------|-----------------------------|
| z-index           | To control the stacking order of positioned elements | `element { z-index: 10; }` |

- Remember: Higher values are on top.
- Default is 0, which means no stacking context.
- Negative values can push elements behind others.

```css
.element {
  position: relative;
  z-index: 10;
}
```

1. Flexbox is a layout model that helps in arranging items in a flexible manner.

| Method or Keyword   | When to use                         | One-line code syntax example       |
|---------------------|-------------------------------------|-------------------------------------|
| flex-direction       | To define the direction of items    | `flex-direction: row;`             |
| flex-wrap           | To control wrapping of items        | `flex-wrap: wrap;`                 |
| justify-content      | To align items along the main axis  | `justify-content: center;`          |
| align-items         | To align items along the cross axis | `align-items: flex-start;`         |
| align-content       | To align flex lines                 | `align-content: space-between;`     |

- Remember: `flex-direction` can be `row`, `column`, `row-reverse`, or `column-reverse`.
- Use `justify-content` for main axis alignment and `align-items` for cross axis alignment.

```css
.container {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: row;
  justify-content: space-between;
  align-items: center;
}
```

To center a div, you can use CSS properties such as flexbox, grid, or table display. Here's a simple example using the table display method:

| Method or Keyword | When to use | One-line code syntax example |
|-------------------|--------------|-----------------------------|
| display: table-cell | When you want to center content vertically and horizontally | .cn { display: table-cell; vertical-align: middle; text-align: center; } |
| display: flex | For modern layouts with responsive designs | .cn { display: flex; justify-content: center; align-items: center; } |
| margin: auto | For block elements with a defined width | .inner { margin: auto; width: 200px; } |

- Remember to set a height for the parent div when using vertical alignment.
- Flexbox is the most versatile method for responsive designs.

```css
.cn {
  display: table-cell;
  width: 500px;
  height: 500px;
  vertical-align: middle;
  text-align: center;
}
.inner {
  display: inline-block;
  width: 200px;
  height: 200px;
}
```

Media properties in CSS allow you to apply styles based on the type of device. They help in creating responsive designs.

| Method or Keyword | When to use                     | One-line code syntax example         |
|-------------------|----------------------------------|-------------------------------------|
| all               | Default for all media types     | `@media all { ... }`               |
| screen            | For computer and mobile screens  | `@media screen { ... }`            |
| print             | For printed documents            | `@media print { ... }`             |
| speech            | For screen readers               | `@media speech { ... }`            |

- Remember: 'all' is the catch-all, 'screen' is for displays, 'print' is for printers, and 'speech' is for audio output.

```css
@media screen {
  body {
    background-color: lightblue;
  }
}
```

CSS Grid Layout is a layout system that allows for the arrangement of elements in a grid format, making it easier to design responsive web pages.

| Method or Keyword | When to use | One-line code syntax example |
|-------------------|-------------|-----------------------------|
| grid-template-columns | To define the number and size of columns in a grid | grid-template-columns: 100px 200px; |
| grid-template-rows | To define the number and size of rows in a grid | grid-template-rows: auto 100px; |
| grid-area | To specify a specific area in the grid for an element | grid-area: header; |

- Remember: Grid is for 2D layouts, Flexbox is for 1D.
- Think of grid as a table layout for web elements.

```css
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
  grid-template-rows: auto;
}
```

The :root selector targets the highest-level parent element in the DOM, which is typically the <html> element. This selector is useful for defining global styles and CSS variables.

| Method or Keyword | When to use | One-line code syntax example |
|-------------------|-------------|-----------------------------|
| :root             | To apply styles to the root element of the document | :root { --main-color: blue; } |

- Remember that :root is the highest level in the DOM.
- It's often used for CSS variables to maintain consistency across styles.

```css
:root {
  --main-color: blue;
  --font-size: 16px;
}
```

CSS variables are custom properties defined in CSS that can be reused throughout your styles. They allow for dynamic styling and can be manipulated with JavaScript.

| Method or Keyword | When to use | One-line code syntax example |
|-------------------|--------------|-----------------------------|
| --custom-property  | When you need dynamic styling | `--main-color: blue;` |
| var()            | To use a CSS variable | `color: var(--main-color);` |

- CSS variables cascade and inherit.
- Preprocessor variables do not.
- CSS variables can be changed at runtime.

```css
:root {
  --main-color: blue;
}

.button {
  background-color: var(--main-color);
}
```

Specificity is a way to calculate which CSS rule will be applied to an element based on the selectors used. It is calculated using a hierarchy: inline styles > IDs > classes/pseudo-classes/attributes > elements/universal selector.

| Method or Keyword | When to use | One-line code syntax example |
|-------------------|-------------|------------------------------|
| Inline styles      | When you want to override all other styles | `<div style='color: red;'>Text</div>` |
| ID selectors       | When you need to apply styles to a unique element | `#myId { color: blue; }` |
| Class selectors    | For styling multiple elements with the same class | `.myClass { font-size: 16px; }` |
| Element selectors   | For styling all elements of a specific type | `div { margin: 10px; }` |

- Remember: Inline > ID > Class > Element
- Use browser dev tools to inspect and understand specificity.

```css
#example {
  color: green;
}
.myClass {
  color: blue;
}
<div id='example' class='myClass'>This text will be green.</div>
```

1. Progressive rendering allows web pages to load content in a way that improves the perceived speed for users.

| Method or Keyword          | When to use                             | One-line code syntax example                                                                 |
|---------------------------|-----------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Intersection Observer API  | To lazy load images as they enter view | `let lazyImageObserver = new IntersectionObserver(callback);`                                   

- Use lazy loading to defer loading of off-screen images.
- Monitor viewport changes to trigger loading.

```javascript
img.classList.add('lazy');
src="placeholder-image.jpg";
data-src="image-to-lazy-load-1x.jpg";
data-srcset="image-to-lazy-load-2x.jpg 2x, image-to-lazy-load-1x.jpg 1x";

document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function() {
  var lazyImages = [...document.querySelectorAll('img.lazy')];
  if ('IntersectionObserver' in window) {
    let lazyImageObserver = new IntersectionObserver(function(entries, observer) {
      entries.forEach(function(entry) {
        if (entry.isIntersecting) {
          let lazyImage = entry.target;
          lazyImage.src = lazyImage.dataset.src;
          lazyImage.srcset = lazyImage.dataset.srcset;
          lazyImage.classList.remove('lazy');
          lazyImageObserver.unobserve(lazyImage);
        }
      });
    });
    lazyImages.forEach(function(lazyImage) {
      lazyImageObserver.observe(lazyImage);
    });
  } else {
    // Possibly fall back to event handlers here
  }
});
```

The overflow property in CSS specifies how content should behave when it overflows its container. When set to hidden, any content that exceeds the container's dimensions is not displayed.

| Method or Keyword | When to use                       | One-line code syntax example               |
|-------------------|-----------------------------------|-------------------------------------------|
| overflow: hidden   | To clip overflowing content        | `div { overflow: hidden; }`              |

- Remember: 'hidden' means 'not visible'.
- Use it for clean designs without scrollbars.

```css
div {
  width: 150px;
  height: 50px;
  overflow: hidden;
}
```

1. Use text-align: center on the parent div for horizontal centering.
2. Apply position: relative on the div and position: absolute on the p tag.
3. Set top, bottom, left, right to 0, and use margin: auto for vertical centering.

| Method or Keyword | When to use | One-line code syntax example |
|-------------------|-------------|-----------------------------|
| text-align        | To center text horizontally | div { text-align: center; } |
| position          | To control element positioning | div { position: relative; } |
| margin            | To center an element vertically | p { margin: auto; } |

- Remember: Relative parent, absolute child.
- Use margin auto for centering vertically.

```css
.div {
  position: relative;
  height: 20vh;
  width: 20vw;
  text-align: center;
}

.p {
  position: absolute;
  top: 0;
  bottom: 0;
  left: 0;
  right: 0;
  margin: auto;
  height: 1.2em;
  width: 20vw;
}
```

1. CSS counters are a way to automatically number elements like headings.

| Method or Keyword   | When to use                         | One-line code syntax example                          |
|---------------------|-------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------|
| counter-reset       | To initialize a counter to a specific value | `counter-reset: header;`                             |
| counter-increment    | To increment the counter value      | `counter-increment: header;`                          |
| content             | To display the counter value        | `content: 'Header ' counter(header) ':';`           |

- Use unique names for counters to avoid conflicts.
- Remember to reset the counter before using it.
- Ensure the counter name is not a CSS keyword.

```css
body {
  counter-reset: header;
}
h2::before {
  counter-increment: header;
  content: 'Header ' counter(header) ':';
}
```

CSS sprites are a technique used to combine multiple images into one larger image file, which reduces the number of HTTP requests needed to load a webpage. This is particularly useful for icons and small graphics used in user interfaces.

| Method or Keyword | When to use | One-line code syntax example |
|-------------------|--------------|------------------------------|
| CSS Sprites       | When you have multiple small images to load | `background-image: url('sprite.png');` |

- Use CSS background positioning to display specific images from the sprite.
- Helps in optimizing the loading time of web pages.

```css
.icon {
  background-image: url('sprite.png');
  background-position: -10px -20px; /* Adjust to show the correct icon */
  width: 50px;
  height: 50px;
}
```

Tweening is the process of filling the gaps between keyframes in CSS animations. It involves generating intermediate frames that create the illusion of smooth motion from one state to another.

| Method or Keyword | When to use | One-line code syntax example |
|-------------------|-------------|-----------------------------|
| @keyframes        | To define the animation sequence | @keyframes slide { from { margin-left: 100px; } to { margin-left: 0; } } |
| animation-duration | To specify the length of the animation | animation-duration: 2s; |
| animation-name    | To assign a name to the animation | animation-name: slide; |

- Remember that keyframes define the start and end points.
- Use transform properties for various effects.

```css
@keyframes slidethrough {
  from {
    margin-left: 100px;
    width: 300px;
  }
  to {
    margin-left: 0;
    width: 100px;
  }
}

p {
  animation-duration: 2s;
  animation-name: slidethrough;
}
```

Adaptive design focuses on developing websites based on multiple fixed layout sizes, while responsive design adapts content based on available browser space.

| Method or Keyword | When to use | One-line code syntax example |
|-------------------|--------------|-----------------------------|
| Adaptive Design    | When you want specific layouts for fixed screen sizes | N/A |
| Responsive Design  | When you want a fluid layout that adjusts to any screen size | N/A |

- Adaptive design typically uses six standard screen widths.
- Responsive design uses CSS media queries for fluid layouts.
- Adaptive design requires more initial effort for layout planning.

```css
/* Example of a media query for responsive design */
@media (max-width: 600px) {
  body {
    background-color: lightblue;
  }
}
```
